{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.89,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1477"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the rural General Practice clinic with a 12-hour history of worsening pain, redness, and decreased vision in her right eye. She had cataract surgery performed three days ago. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her medications include perindopril and metformin. She has no relevant social, occupational, or travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Ocular examination reveals marked conjunctival injection, a hazy cornea, hypopyon, and reduced visual acuity in the right eye. The left eye is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ciprofloxacin","Outpatient ophthalmology review","Urgent ophthalmology review","Topical corticosteroid drops","Lubricating eye drops"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has classic features of endophthalmitis following recent intraocular surgery, including pain, redness, hypopyon, and rapid visual loss. Endophthalmitis is a vision-threatening emergency that requires immediate ophthalmology input for intravitreal antibiotics and possible vitreous sampling to maximise the chance of preserving vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent ophthalmology review\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. The ophthalmologist will administer intravitreal antibiotics and may perform vitreous sampling for culture. Early intervention is critical to prevent permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate, as oral antibiotics alone are insufficient for endophthalmitis. Systemic antibiotics have poor penetration into the vitreous cavity, and any delay in definitive therapy can result in irreversible vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid drops\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect as initial management. While steroids may be used later as adjunctive therapy, they should not be given without concurrent antibiotics as they may worsen infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELubricating eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate, as this would delay urgent treatment for a potentially blinding condition. The patient\u0027s symptoms are not consistent with simple dry eye or post-operative irritation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutpatient ophthalmology review\u003C/strong\u003E is not suitable, as endophthalmitis requires immediate assessment and intervention. Delaying treatment even by hours can significantly worsen the visual prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndophthalmitis is a severe inflammation of the intraocular cavities, most often due to infection. It typically occurs after intraocular surgery (such as cataract extraction), penetrating eye trauma, or, less commonly, via haematogenous spread from systemic infection. The most common causative organisms are \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus epidermidis\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E. Clinical features include rapid onset of pain, decreased vision, conjunctival injection, hypopyon, and a hazy cornea. Without urgent intervention with early recognition, permanent vision loss is likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endophthalmitis is a vision-threatening emergency that requires urgent ophthalmology review and intravitreal antibiotics.","Recent intraocular surgery or penetrating eye trauma are key risk factors for endophthalmitis.","Prompt recognition and early intervention are critical to prevent permanent vision loss."],"references":["Simakurthy S, Tripathy K. Endophthalmitis. [Updated 2023 Aug 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559079/","Durand ML. Endophthalmitis. Clin Microbiol Infect. 2013 Mar;19(3):227-34. doi: 10.1111/1469-0691.12118. PMID: 23438028; PMCID: PMC3638360. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23438028/","Sheu SJ. Endophthalmitis. Korean J Ophthalmol. 2017 Aug;31(4):283-289. doi: 10.3341/kjo.2017.0036. Epub 2017 Jun 28. PMID: 28752698; PMCID: PMC5540982. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28752698/","Safneck JR. Endophthalmitis: A review of recent trends. Saudi J Ophthalmol. 2012 Apr;26(2):181-9. doi: 10.1016/j.sjopt.2012.02.011. Epub 2012 Mar 3. PMID: 23960990; PMCID: PMC3729827. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3729827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T15:02:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T15:02:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111872"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"htt